basicQuestions.answerText:
Many cases of Behr syndrome have been found to result from <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK5191/def-item/homozygote/" target="_blank">homozygous</a> or <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK5191/def-item/compound-heterozygote/" target="_blank">compound heterozygous</a> <a href="http://www.genome.gov/Glossary/index.cfm?id=134" target="_blank">mutations</a>&nbsp;in the <em><a href="http://www.omim.org/entry/605290" target="_blank">OPA1</a></em> gene.[2412][11768] This gene provides instructions for making a protein that helps determine the shape and structure of mitochondria, the energy-producing centers within cells. The OPA1 protein is made in many types of cells and tissues, including the brain, the light-sensitive tissue at the back of the eye (the retina), muscles used for movement (skeletal muscles), the liver, and the heart.[11769] It is unclear why people with mutations in the OPA1 gene develop the symptoms of Behr syndrome. <br />
<br />
A few additional cases of Behr syndrome have been attributed to mutations in the <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/OPA3#conditions" target="_blank">OPA3</a></em>, <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/C12orf65" target="_blank">C12ORF65</a></em> and <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/C19orf12" target="_blank">C19ORF12</a></em> genes.[11768] &nbsp;
